metadata.name: life is a (beautiful) mess #94
metadata.description:
when carefully applied, chaos brings things to life.

'life is a (beautiful) mess' was created as i led a certain amount of chaos take control of an animated textile algorithm i'm developing. 
as soon as it happened i realized that it was a great representation of our lives. 
each line represents one of us and the patterns that appear repeatedly are the situations we live which make us move, feel and be in a certain way. 
the image created is the sum of our paths in this life, as they only make sense when we look at them as one.

---

i hope you find it pleasant to watch this animation, how it develops and grows during aprox 1'30"
there are pieces drawn with the 4 typical school pen colors: black, green, blue and red. also a multicolor and a rare dark mode features.


press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the animation
doubleclick the mouse to resume the animation

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: Boom_fx_max #182
metadata.description:
Boom_fx_max, by Stephen Boyd  
August, 2022  
Little India, Toronto, Canada.

This is a free mint for anyone who is a holder of Boom_fx as of August 31, 2022, 00:11:00Z. 

Signed 18" x 12" or 12" x 12" prints are available to holders for both Boom_fx and Boom_fx_max tokens on request. Please send a DM for more information.

Any unclaimed reserves will be released after four days and available at a price to be determined. 


Project Description
---
Boom_fx_max uses all eleven days of data in one image. This constitutes 4,567 earthquakes being represented in every output. This differs from the original Boom_fx which used hours of time on one of the eleven days and typically included a few hundred seismic events.

There are eleven new colour palettes and seven different ratios to organize relationships between visual elements.

The earthquake data comes from the USGS API. There is further documentation (./documentation/Information_about_boom_fx_max.md) included with this project that outlines how this data was collected and the information included in these feeds.


Three Features
---
1. Aspect ratios:
   - Landscape
   - Portrait
   - Square
2. Eleven colour palettes
3. Seven Organizing Principle Ratios:
   - Super Golden Ratio
   - PHI
   - Golden Angle
   - Silver Ratio
   - Euler's Number
   - Reciprocal Fibonacci Constant
   - Feigenbaum Constant


Interaction
---
Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press t: thumbnail @ a maximum pixel width or height of 200px
- Press s: your current screen size
- Press p: print size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 4800px which is 16"@300dpi
- Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ a maximum pixel width or height of 2160px
- Press m: Max size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 10800px.

The filename will include some metadata such as the unique hash, date and time at time of capture.


Appreciation
---
Thank you to everyone who has collected one my pieces.

Thank you to the USGS for making this data available.

And thank you the most to KIRH.


Data Sources, Software Libraries and VCS / Source Code
--- 
Data Sources
All earthquake data is sourced from the USGS Earthquake API for the International Federation of Digital Seismograph Networks (FDSN). 

Software Libraries Used
Made with Processing / P5.js

metadata.name: Roasting Humans #187
metadata.description:
========
Concept
========
Humanists live in a world built on human bones.
The fuel of humanism is human sacrifices.

Eating flesh is natural for animals.
But humans are eating  life energy, results of work, time  of other humans.

Social status is in general about how many humans you personally can devour.
Personal freedom in general about how not to be eaten by other humans.

Sweet promises, beautiful concepts, inspiring ideas - basically ways to put  the victim on the skewer.

Humanism today is an attempt to inject anesthesia into the basic process of eating others.
Slavery must be gentle and invisible.
Weapons must be lethal and not cause suffering.
People should be polite and tolerant.
You must not feel that your blood is being sucked out.

If the victim does not feel the pain and does not scream: is the victim a plant? Is predator a vegan?

Is it better to you feel pain or inject anesthesia?
Anesthesia today is not only drugs, but entertainment.

Are you enjoy of eating others?
So check if you are on a skewer and how roasted you are.

==============
Technical Details
==============
Mangal size calculating depending on humans amount (min=5; max=111) and skewer parameters.

You can roast the bodies from different sides using the control buttons.
The bodies are divided into sectors that absorb thermal energy differently depending on the angle of rotation.
The amount of absorbed energy determines the degree of roasting.
The camera is focused on the active skewer, to select another one, press the button or select from the list.

Press the left mouse button to rotate the point of view.
Hold down the right mouse button to move the point of view.

metadata.name: Simple_Syrup_1 #63
metadata.description:
Simple_Syrup_1, by Stephen Boyd
May, 2022
Little India, Toronto, Canada.


_Project Description
"The staple cocktail sweetener more than earns its name, consisting, simply, of equal-parts granulated sugar and water. From there, the variations are endless."
https://www.liquor.com/recipes/simple-syrup/


"The variations are endless..." I think of simple syrup as an analogy for what I've seen during my brief time so far on fxhash. The combination of a platform and people bringing out endless variations of creativity. Each Project with the possibility for endless variation in the exploration of a limited number of features.

This is my first project released on fxhash. I'm grateful to everyone who founded fxhash and to everyone who has positively contributed to the community.

These images are comprised of clusters of coloured ellipses on a coloured background. Each cluster varies in their strokeWeight, position, transparency and colour values.

There are two primary variables that all other features are dependent on: the first being the number of clusters, and the second is the number of ellipses in each cluster (up to a maximum of 123 per cluster). From these two variables the rest of the visual attributes (eg. alpha vs strokeWeight, colour palettes, etc...) are determined.

A constant in all my work, including this project, is the use of PHI and a Fibonnaci sequence starting with 4 and 7 to determine layouts and relationships between elements in the image. If you look through the code you will find many instances of the numbers: 4, 7, 11, 18, 29, 47,....

There are 18 colour palettes for this project. They are adapted from Mark Rothko paintings as interpreted by Merritt Smith, (https://mmerrittsmith.github.io/about/). I refactored the original R files to work with Javascript here. You can find Merritt's original project on GitHub: https://github.com/mmerrittsmith/rothko .


_Interaction
You can export this image to PNG format at several different sizes.

I've added code that will re-render the iteration at each of the sizes listed below while retaining its exact characteristics. This is considerably better than trying to up or downscale an image.

Press t: thumbnail @ 200x200 
Press s: your current screen size 
Press p: print size @ 4800x4800 which is 16"@300dpi 
Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ 2160x2160 
Press m: Max size @ 10800x10800 This is a biiiig size


_Technology Used for Development
Made with Processing / P5.js
p5.js v1.4.1 February 02, 2022

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #163
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Tesseract #115
metadata.description:
'Tesseract' is a generative collection drawing on the concept of the cube from oneirology, the interpretation of dreams. In many mythologies and fields of study, the square is considered a 'perfect shape', thus with its abstraction into three isometric dimensions, the cube is seen by some as a representation of the various aspects of the human condition.

In 'Tesseract', the ribbons flowing between the cubes represent the shared experiences that connect us all. No matter how different our lives might be, we all go through the same joys, sorrows, trials, tribulations and experience attachments of varying degrees. 

It is these experiences that bind us together and make us who we are. With these concepts in mind, viewers are invited to interpret each composition as it relates to them and their unique story, from the perspective of that which has been and that which is yet to be experienced.

Press 'S' to save a high resolution PNG at 2400 x 3396 px.

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 1 #413
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ 0.1, ____ 0.2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.
